06368nam a22008415i 9780824845063DE-B159720210729020517.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210729t20032003hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248450637 a10.1515/97808248450632doi  a(DE-B1597)484536  a(OCoLC)1013944019  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aBL1975 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a200/.95124/922300aReligion in Modern Taiwan :bTradition and Innovation in a Changing Society /ced. by Charles B. Jones, Philip Clart. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- t1. Religion in Taiwan at the End of the Japanese Colonial Period -- t2. Stability and Change in Taiwan’s Religious Culture -- t3. Carrying Confucianism into the Modern World: The Taiwan Case -- t4. Chinese Tradition and Taiwanese Modernity: Morality Books as Social Commentary and Critique -- t5. The Cult of the Royal Lords in Postwar Taiwan -- t6. The Daoist Priesthood and Secular Society: Two Aspects of Postwar Taiwanese Daoism -- t7. Religious Change and Democratization in Postwar Taiwan: Mainstream Buddhist Organizations and the Kuomintang, 1947–1996 -- t8. Guanyin Narratives—Wartime and Postwar -- t9. Christianity and Democratization in Modern Taiwan: The Presbyterian Church and the Struggle for Minnan/Hakka Selfhood in the Republic of China -- t10. Accepting the Best, Revealing the Difference— Borrowing and Identity in an Ami Village -- t11. Gods, Ghosts, and Ancestors: Religious Studies and the Question of “Taiwanese Identity” -- tGlossary -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aReligion in Modern Taiwan takes a new look at Taiwan's current religious traditions and their fortunes during the twentieth century. Beginning with the cession of Taiwan to Japan in 1895 and the currents of modernization that accompanied it, the essays move on to explore the developments that have taken place as Buddhists, Daoists, Christians, non-Han aborigines, and others have confronted, resisted, and adapted to (even thrived in) the many upheavals of the modern period. An overview of Taiwan's current religious scene is followed by a comprehensive look at the state of religion in the country prior to the end of World War II and the return of Taiwan to Chinese sovereignty. The remaining essays probe aspects of change within individual religious traditions. The final chapter analyzes changes that took place in the scholarly study and interpretation of religion in Taiwan during the course of the twentieth century. Religion in Modern Taiwan will be read with interest by students and scholars of Chinese religion, religion in Taiwan, the modern history of Taiwan, and by those concerned with issues of religion and modernization. Contributors: Chang Hsun, Philip Clart, Shiun-wey Huang, Christian Jochim, Charles B. Jones, Paul Katz, André Laliberté, Lee Fong-mao, Randall Nadeau, Julian Pas, Barbara Reed, Murray A. Rubinstein.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh1 aClart, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClart, Philip, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFong-mao, Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsun, Chang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJochim, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Charles B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Charles B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKatz, Paul R., econtri